               <note>
                  <ab type="description">Gorgorā is a peninsula on the north of the Lake<placeName ref="LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</placeName>. It is <width>12 km</width> wide in its
                     southern part and stands on a strategical location, an elevated rocky
                     promontory overlooking the lake and next to a series of islands suitable for
                     providing shelter. The peninsula is located in today's <placeName ref="LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmhārā</placeName> Regional State while it once formed
                     part of <placeName ref="LOC2481Dambey">Dambǝyā</placeName>.
                     Gorgorā gained its prominence under the Jesuits as a missionary residence and a
                     major Catholic church thanks to a land grant offered by <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos">Susǝnyos</persName> in <date>1607</date>. In
                        <date>1611</date>, <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos">Susǝnyos</persName>
                     established a <placeName>katamā</placeName> in Gorgorā and in <date>1621</date>
                     he asked the Jesuits to build a royal palace to the south-west, in an area that
                     became known as <placeName>New Gorgorā</placeName>. After the restoration of
                     Orthodoxy, <placeName>New Gorgorā</placeName> was the first residence to be
                     abandoned by the missionaries and, in <date>1665</date>, <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> ordered the burning of the
                     "books of Franks". The Italians seized the Gorgorā peninsula on <date>14 April
                        1936</date> and in <date>1938</date> inaugurated the <placeName>Faro della
                        Conquista</placeName> on the <placeName>Vetta Mussolini</placeName>.</ab>
               </note>
            </place>
